answers.body_markdown:
When you have code written somewhere else but you want TypeScript to know about, you need to [`declare` its type definitions somewhere](https://www.typescriptlang.org/docs/handbook/declaration-files/by-example.html).  Often you put these in their own dedicated library files, but you can use do inline declarations as well.

For example, you could declare it as a `class`, but you need to declare its property/methods also:

    declare class Events implements IEvents {
        $on(event: string, listener: () =&gt; {}): void;
        $once(event: string, listener: () =&gt; {}): void;
        $off(event: string, listener: () =&gt; {}): void;
        $emit(event: string): void;
    }

Or you can declare it is a type and a value, where the type corresponds to the instance side of the class, and the value represents the static side including the constructor.  This is often done in standard libraries, where you will see something like a `Foo` type and `FooConstructor` type, and a variable called `Foo` of the type `FooConstructor`.  (e.g., for `Array` you have [`interface Array&lt;T&gt; {...}`](https://github.com/Microsoft/TypeScript/blob/v3.6.3/lib/lib.es5.d.ts#L1205) for the instance side, [`interface ArrayConstructor`](https://github.com/Microsoft/TypeScript/blob/v3.6.3/lib/lib.es5.d.ts#L1357) for the static side, and [`declare var Array: ArrayConstructor;`](https://github.com/Microsoft/TypeScript/blob/v3.6.3/lib/lib.es5.d.ts#L1368) to show that there&#39;s an object named `Array` that acts as a constructor).  Here&#39;s how you might do it for `Events`:

    interface Events extends IEvents { }
